                                                      • W1 (9.1)

                                                      HG System

                                                      Consider dxdt=Ax where A is a 2x2 real matrix and x is a 2-vector

                                                      • Given an initial vector x(0):=x(0), there must exist a unique solution – a vector function x=x(t)

                                                        This function can be viewed as a parametric representation for a curve in the x1x2-plane, or a trajectory traversed by a moving particle whose velocity dx/dt is specified by the differential equation.

                                                        The x1x2-plane itself is called the phase plane, and a representative set of trajectories is referred to as a phase portrait.

                                                      • If x(0)=0→, then the solution is fixed at 0→ since the derivative would be 0. This point is called the equilibrium point.

                                                        If it is stable, then all solutions will converge onto this point. It is unstable, then all solutions will diverge from it.

                                                      • If x(0)≠0→, then Ax=0→ iff detA=0⟹ad−bc=0⟹ab=cd

                                                        Letting h=ab=cd, we have

                                                        dxdt=Ax=[ax1+bx2cx1+dx2]dx1dt=ax1+bx2=b(hx1+x2)dx2dt=cx1+dx2=d(hx1+x2)dx2dt/dx1dt=d/b=:k

                                                        And integrating dx2dt=kdx1dt we have x2=kx1+C which means the solution is linear with slope k. Given C, the line passes through (0,C)

                                                      • We assume detA≠0⟺Ax≠0, so x(0)=0 is the only equilibrium point, called critical point

                                                      Real distinct roots, same sign

                                                      x=c1 er1tξ(1)+c2 er2tξ(2)dxdt=c1 er1tr1ξ(1)⏟+c2 er2tr2ξ(2)⏟=c1er1tAξ(1)⏟+c2er2tAξ(2)⏟sinceAξ(1)=r1ξ(1),Aξ(2)=r2ξ(2)=A[c1er1tξ(1)+c2er2tξ(2)]=Ax

                                                      • nodal source (positive roots): as t→∞,x→∞ for all x, so it is asymptotically unstable (even if only 1 solution goes to infinity)

                                                      • nodal sink (negative roots): as t→∞,x→0, so it is asymptotically stable

                                                      • to visualize the solutions, use ξ1,ξ2 as new basis vectors: x=c1 er1tξ1+c2 er2tξ2=y1ξ1+y2ξ2

                                                        assume r1<r2, then let α=c2c1,β=r2r1>1, so y2=αy1β

                                                        plotting this with arbitrary α and fixed β, we get parabolic trajectories (nodal sink below):

                                                      Real distinct roots, dif signs

                                                      • saddle point:

                                                        assuming r1<0<r2, then as t→∞,er1t→0,er2t→∞

                                                        so unless c2=0, x=c1 er1tξ(1)+c2 er2tξ(2)→∞, which is unstable

                                                      • to visualize, rewrite as y2=αy1−β

                                                      Duplicate roots

                                                      • proper node/star point (2 eigenvectors): x=c1 er1tξ1+c2 er2tξ2

                                                        If r < 0, then x→0 (stable); if r>0, then x→∞ (unstable)

                                                      • improper/degenerate node (1 eigenvector): x=c1ξert+c2(ξtert+ηert)←Solve for η using (A−rI)η=ξ

                                                        If r < 0, then x→0 (stable); if r>0, then x→∞ (unstable)

                                                      • To visualize, write x=c1ertξ+c2(tertξ+ertη)=ert(c1+c2t)⏟y1ξ+ertc2⏟y2η=y1ξ+y2η

                                                        Semi-axes? Take c2=0,c1=1 and -1. So y2=0,y1=ertc1

                                                        Tangent to which axis? Take c2≠0. If |y1|≫|y2|, then the trajectory is tangent to the ξ axis

                                                        Tangent to which semi-axis? Since sgn y1=sgn c2,sgn y2=sgn c2, we know that y1>0 for vectors in the same half plane as η, and y1<0 in the other half plane. Similarly for y2. So the trajectories in the half plane y2>0 are tangent to the positive ξ semi-axis at the origin.

                                                      Complex roots, non-zero real part

                                                      Plug ξ=u+iv into Aξ=(λ+iμ⏟r)ξ

                                                      A(u+iv)=(λ+iμ)(u+iv)Au+iAv=(λu−μv)+i(μu+λv)Au=λu−μvAv=μu+λv

                                                      The RHS can be written as [λμ−μλ][uv]

                                                      dxdt=Ax[x1′x2′]=[λμ−μλ][x1x2]x1′=λx1+μx2x2′=−μx1+λx2

                                                      Use polar coordinates. First differentiate r2=x12+x22

                                                      (r2)′=2x1x1′+2x2x2′2rr′=2x1(λx1+μx2)+2x2(−μx1+λx2)rr′=λ(x12+x22)=λr2r′=λr

                                                      Solve drdt=λr (separable ODE) to get r=Ceλt where C≥0 is an arbitrary constant.

                                                      Now differentiate tan⁡θ=x2x1 to get θ′=−μ, so θ=−μt+θ0

                                                      (tan⁡θ)′=x1x2′−x2x1′x12=x1(−μx1+λx2)−x2(λx1+μx2)x12θ′cos2⁡θ=−μ(x12+x22)x12=−μr2x12=−μ1x12r2=−μ1cos2⁡θθ′=−μ
                                                      • spiral sink (negative real part): λ<0⟹r→0⟹x→0, so it is asymptotically stable
                                                      • spiral source (positive real part): λ>0⟹r→∞⟹x→∞, so it is unstable

                                                      Complex roots, zero real part

                                                      • center: λ=0⟹r=Ceλt=0 is a circle centered at the origin. It is stable, but not asymptotically stable.

                                                      NHG System

                                                      If given dxdt=Ax−b, then let x=x(0)+u where u is a new unknown vector.

                                                      Sub it in: dxdt=A(x(0)+u)−b=dudt

                                                      Kill the NHG term by solving Ax(0)=b so that the above becomes Au=dudt

                                                      The solution x(0) is the equilibrium point.

                                                      Plotting Phase Portraits

                                                      1. Plot the eigen vectors as secondary axes at th

                                                        Their directions are determined by the sign of r. If positive, point away from origin.

                                                      2. Draw trajectories.

                                                        • if real, distinct roots:

                                                          • dif signs: saddle; just follow the directions on the secondary axes (4 curves, i.e).
                                                          • same signs: node; see which axis has a bigger eigen value |r| (means faster convergence), make the trajectory parallel to that axis and curve it towards the other axis until it's tangent, then make a U-turn (trace a parabola)

                                                        • if duplicate roots:

                                                          • 2 eigen vectors: proper node/star point; just draw straight lines through the origin.
                                                          • 1 eigen vector: improper node; arrow test: go to (1, 0) and plot A[10], if unclear go to (0, 1) and plot A[01] and connect/follow the arrow(s)

                                                        • if complex roots:

                                                          • non-zero real part: spiral; arrow test
                                                          • purely imaginary: circle; arrow test

                                                      W2 (9.2-9.4)

                                                      Autonomous Systems

                                                      We have 2 diff eq'ns of the form dxdt=F(x,y),dydt=G(x,y)

                                                      There exists a unique solution x=x(t),y=y(t) satisfying the initial conditions x(t0)=x0,y(t0)=y0

                                                      In vector form, dxdt=f(x)=[F(x,y)G(x,y)] and there exists a solution x=[x(t)y(t)] satisfying the initial cond. x(t0)=x0=[x0y0]

                                                      Since F,G do not depend on t, the system is said to be autonomous.

                                                      An autonomous system has an associated direction field that is indep of time.

                                                      Note Solutions that satisfy the same initial condition must lie on the same trajectory.

                                                      Stability at Critical Points

                                                      At a critical point, f(x)=0 and x′=0

                                                      Critical points are important because they correspond to equilibrium solutions (where x(t) and y(t) are constant). These solutions determine the behavior of trajectories throughout the phase plane.

                                                      Stable: given ϵ>0, there exists δ>0 such that if ∥x(0)−x(0)∥<δ, then

                                                      ∥x(t)−x(0)∥<ϵ ∀ t

                                                      Asymptotically stable: given ϵ>0, there exists δ>0 such that if ∥x(0)−x(0)∥<δ, then as t→∞

                                                      ∥x(t)−x(0)∥→0

                                                      Note Asymptotic stability ⟹ stability. The converse is false.

                                                      For the linear system dxdt=Ax, ❓ dif in the TB for stable case (P408 thm)

                                                      • stable if r1,r2≤0 are real, or if r1=λ+iμ,μ≠0,λ≤0
                                                      • asymp. stable if r1,r2<0 are real, or if r1=λ+iμ,μ≠0,λ<0

                                                      Oscillating Pendulum

                                                      The following models a pendulum's angular momentum about the origin.

                                                      d2θdt2+γdθdt+ω2sin⁡θ=0

                                                      γ=cmL is the damping force (m is the mass, L is the length of the pendulum), ω2=gL

                                                      We can convert it to an autonomous system of 2 first-order equations by letting x=θ,y=dθdt, so

                                                      dxdt=dθdt=ydydt=d2θdt2=−γdθdt−ω2sin⁡θ=−γy−ω2sin⁡x

                                                      Linearization

                                                      Given dxdt=Ax+b, find the critical point:

                                                      Ax(0)+b=0,Ax(0)=−b,x(0)=−A−1b

                                                      Variable change:

                                                      x=x(0)+u

                                                      So we have

                                                      dudt=dxdt=Ax+b=A(x(0)+u)+b=Ax(0)+Au+b=−b+Au+b=Au

                                                      Local Linearization

                                                      Let x(0)=(x(0),y(0)) be a critical point, i.e.

                                                      F(x(0),y(0))=0G(x(0),y(0))=0

                                                      Use Taylor expansion, discard the error terms and write in vector form:

                                                      f(x,y)=[F(x,y)G(x,y)]≃J[x−x0y−y0]=J(x−x(0))

                                                      where J is the Jacobian at x(0):

                                                      J=[Fx(x0,y0)Fy(x0,y0)Gx(x0,y0)Gy(x0,y0)]

                                                      Variable change:

                                                      x−x(0)=u⟺{x−x0=u1y−y0=u2

                                                      Then we have

                                                      dudt=dxdt=f(x,y)≃J(x−x(0))=Ju

                                                      Note This method only works in the vicinity of the critical point (hence "local" linearization).

                                                      Summary Table

                                                      Competing Species

                                                      The following yields 4 critical points

                                                      dxdt=x(ϵ1−σ1x−α1y)dydt=y(ϵ2−σ2x−α2y)

                                                      Predator Prey System

                                                      The following yields 2 critical points (saddle and center)

                                                      dxdt=x(a−αy)dydt=y(−c+γx)

                                                      It is integrable:

                                                      (−c+γx)dxx=(a−αy)dyy−γx−αy+clog⁡x+alog⁡y=C

                                                      Plotting Phase Portraits

                                                      If given a system, plot the behavior at each critical point first. Then combine to form the big picture.

                                                      Separatrix:

                                                      Let P be a point in the xy-plane with the property that a trajectory passing through P ultimately approaches the critical point as t → ∞. Then this trajectory is said to be attracted by the critical point.

                                                      The set of all such points P is called the basin of attraction or the region of asymptotic stability of the critical point.

                                                      A trajectory that bounds a basin of attraction is called a separatrix because it separates trajectories that approach a particular critical point from trajectories that do not.

                                                      W3, 4 (Ch6)

                                                      Comparison Test for Convergence

                                                      If f is piecewise continuous for t≥a, if |f(t)|≤g(t) when t≥M for some positive constant M, and if ∫M∞g(t)dt converges, then ∫a∞f(t)dt also converges.

                                                      On the other hand, if f(t)≥g(t)≥0 for t≥M, and if ∫M∞g(t)dt diverges, then ∫a∞f(t)dt also diverges.

                                                      Integral Transform

                                                      A relation of the form F(s)=∫abK(s,t)f(t)dt where f is transformed into F by K(s,t), the kernel of the transformation. F is said to be the transform of f.

                                                      Laplace Transform

                                                      L{f(t)}=F(s)=∫0∞e−stf(t)dt exists if

                                                      • f is piecewise continuous on 0≤t≤A ∀ A>0
                                                      • ∃ K,a,M∈R such that |f(t)|≤Keat when t≥M

                                                      To use it to solve a diff eq'n:

                                                      1. Transform an initial value problem for an unknown function f in the t-domain into a simpler problem for F in the s-domain.
                                                      2. Solve it to find F.
                                                      3. Invert the transform - recover the desired function f from its transform F.

                                                      Inverse Transform

                                                      1. multiply numerator by denominator

                                                      Initial Value Problem

                                                      L{f′(t)}=sL{f(t)}−f(0) exists for s>a if

                                                      • f is continuous, and f′ is piecewise continuous on any interval 0≤t≤A
                                                      • ∃ K,a,M s.t. |f(t)|≤Keat ∀ t≥M

                                                      Extending to the second derivative:

                                                      L{f′′(t)}=sL{f′(t)}−f′(0)=s(sL{f(t)}−f(0))−f′(0)=s2L{f(t)}−sf(0)−f′(0)

                                                      Provided the function f and its derivatives satisfy suitable conditions, an expression for the transform of the nth  derivative f(n) can be derived by n successive applications of this theorem. The result is given in the following corollary.

                                                      Suppose that the functions f,f′,…,f(n−1) are continuous and that f(n) is piecewise continuous on any interval 0≤t≤A. Suppose further that there exist constants K,a, and M such that |f(t)|≤Keat,|f′(t)|≤Keat,…,|f(n−1)(t)|≤Keat for t≥M. Then L{f(n)(t)} exists for s>a and is given by

                                                      L{f(n)(t)}=snL{f(t)}−sn−1f(0)−⋯−sf(n−2)(0)−f(n−1)(0)

                                                      General Second-Order Linear Eq'n

                                                      ay″+by′+cy=f(t)a(s2Y(s)−sy(0)−y′(0))+b(sY(s)−y(0))+cY(s)=F(s)

                                                      Heaviside (Unit Step) Function

                                                      uc(t)={0,t<c1,t≥c

                                                      The Laplace transform of uc for c≥0 is easily determined:

                                                      L{uc(t)}=∫0∞e−stuc(t)dt=∫c∞e−stdt=e−css,s>0.

                                                      Since u0(t)=1 for all t≥0, we have that

                                                      L{u0(t)}=e0s=1s=L{1}

                                                      For a given function f defined for t≥0, we will often want to consider the related function g defined by

                                                      g(t)={0,t<cf(t−c),t≥c,

                                                      which represents a translation of f a distance c in the positive t direction.

                                                      Making use of the unit step function, we can write g(t) in the form

                                                      g(t)=uc(t)f(t−c)

                                                      Translation Thm

                                                      The translation of f(t) a distance c in the positive t direction corresponds to the multiplication of F(s) by e−cs

                                                      If the Laplace transform of f(t),F(s)=L{f(t)}, exists for s>a≥0, and if c is a positive constant, then

                                                      L{uc(t)f(t−c)}=e−csL{f(t)}=e−csF(s),s>a

                                                      Conversely, if f(t) is the inverse Laplace transform of F(s),f(t)=L−1{F(s)}, then

                                                      uc(t)f(t−c)=L−1{e−csF(s)}

                                                      Multiplication of f(t) by ect results in a translation of the transform F(s) a distance c in the positive s direction

                                                      If the Laplace transform of f(t),F(s)=L{f(t)}, exists for s>a≥0, and if c is a constant, then

                                                      L{ectf(t)}=F(s−c),s>a+c.

                                                      Conversely, if f(t)=L−1{F(s)}, then

                                                      ectf(t)=L−1{F(s−c)}
